	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Website established in Jamaica to assist exporters in accessing regional markets </h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to a press release from the Jamaican Information Service in September 2013, the Private Sector Organization of Jamaica has launched a website to provide local exporters with “greater access to information on existing and potential markets within the Caribbean”. The initiative is being financed through the Caribbean Development Bank’s Caribbean Aid for Trade and Regional Integration Trust Fund with funding from the UK Department for International Development.</p><p>The website provides information on “tariff and non-tariff measures, including information on customs tariff and clearance fees, as well as customs procedures and documentation..., additional duties and taxes, measures related to the importation of services and… contact details for the relevant authorities dealing with import/export procedures for each CARICOM member state”.</p><p>According to Jamaica’s Commerce Minister, “the website will allow business leaders to make prudent decisions through the provision of essential information, which must be factored into those decisions.” Currently the website focuses on CARICOM countries, but “the content is expected to be expanded in the future to include information on other countries.”</p><p>The importance of this initiative is illustrated by a recent survey by the International Trade Centre of 500 export businesses in Trinidad and Tobago. The survey found that agro-food products are the items most affected by non-tariff measures (NTMs), with the majority of problems related to delays in obtaining required health, sanitary and phytosanitary certificates. This is significant, since Trinidad is the major manufacturer and exporter of agri-food products in CARICOM.</p><p>The study made the following policy recommendations to address NTMs:</p>
<ul>

<li>strengthen inspection and other certification processes at key government agencies by upgrading systems;</li>

<li>review current bottlenecks;</li>

<li>set up public–private sector committees to address broad trade facilitation issues;</li>

<li>continue with improvements in customs and at port procedures;</li>

<li>expand and upgrade testing laboratories to meet international standards, and build stronger, national-quality infrastructure to support the work of testing laboratories;</li>

<li>increase representation of businesses in foreign markets by conducting market surveys, providing market intelligence and establishing trade facilitation offices in selected markets; and</li>

<li>prioritise and enact legislation to support trade, in part by removing outdated legislation.</li>

</ul>
<p>The study also identified a number of policy issues to be addressed within CARICOM, including:</p>
<ul>

<li>lengthy product registration procedures;</li>

<li>complex labelling requirements; </li>

<li>excessive certification requirements; </li>

<li>inconsistent rules for certificates of origin and customs procedures;</li>

<li>delays in obtaining suspension and safeguard certificates.&nbsp;</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Jamaica Information Service, ‘CARICOM website gives market access to local exporters”, 23 September 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/article/113405/Jamaica-Caricom-website-gives-market-access-to-local-exporters #SlideFrame_1" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/article/113405/Jamaica-Caricom-website-gives-m...</a></p><p>International Trade Centre (ITC), ‘Trinidad and Tobago face most NTMs from CARICOM countries’, 12 August 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.intracen.org/news/Trinidad-and-Tobago-face-most-NTMs-from-CARICOM-countries/" target="_self">http://www.intracen.org/news/Trinidad-and-Tobago-face-most-NTMs-from-CAR...</a></p><p>ITC, ‘Trinidad and Tobago: Company perspectives – An ITC series on non-tariff measures’, 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.intracen.org/uploadedFiles/intracen.org/Content/About_ITC/Press/Articles/NTM%20Trinidad%20and%20Tobago%20for%20web(2).pdf" target="_self">http://www.intracen.org/uploadedFiles/intracen.org/Content/About_ITC/Pre...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The initiative of the Private Sector Organization of Jamaica is in keeping with CARICOM’s goal of facilitating inter-regional trade. There is a growing consensus that – in addition to the problem of regional transportation connections – problems arise from a lack of knowledge and awareness of the market access requirements of CARICOM member states, as well as the absence of bilateral trade protocols, particularly for fresh and processed agricultural products. </p><p>In 2012, a Ministerial Sub-Committee on the Facilitation of Agricultural Trade was established, endorsed by the CARICOM Council for Trade and Economic Development. The Sub-Committee has an explicit mandate to address the use of non-tariff measures on trade between CARICOM members. As a first step towards removing trade barriers, Ministers have called for an inventory of the NTMs – both official and non-official measures – used in the region, and an assessment of current intra-regional trade flows. </p><p>Recently, individual governments have been engaging in bilateral negotiations on specific export products as a means of addressing NTMs. CARICOM has also drafted an administrative protocol to guide and facilitate inter-regional trade in animal products.</p><p>The type of initiative launched in Jamaica has been tried before, but faced problems in obtaining clear and unambiguous information and data. This was in part linked to a lack of coordination among government departments. </p><p>Experience in other ACP regions suggests that once an information service has been established, broader initiatives will be required, including online real-time reporting mechanisms on the application of NTMs and, subsequently, the establishment of transparent, accountable and ultimately binding mechanisms for resolving disputes over the application of NTMs.</p><p>The establishment of such a mechanism would carry significance beyond CARICOM, as the need mechanisms for resolving disputes over the application of NTMs is an increasingly important issue in ACP trade with major OECD partners.</p><p>Establishing a transparent, accountable and binding mechanism for resolving disputes over the application of NTMs at the regional level in the Caribbean could give a lead internationally to efforts to promote similar arrangements under both inter-regional trade agreements and at the multilateral level (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Calls-for-a-right-to-development-and-a-right-to-trade-to-be-enshrined-in-WTO-rules" target="_blank">Calls for “a right to development” and “a right to trade” to be enshrine...</a>’, 11 October 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
